The paper deals with deep convolutional neural networks (DCNNs) and their application to computer vision tasks. Specifically, it focuses on the use of synthetic images to train DCNNs, which is a topic that falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of DCNNs for few-shot learning, which is a topic that falls under the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper explores the invariances of DCNNs to object-class variations caused by 3D shape, pose, and photorealism, which is a topic that falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of crowdsourced 3D CAD models, which is a topic that falls under the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of DCNNs for adaptive training, which is a topic that falls under the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category.
